In the second place, because it was the capital os the empire; and on this account it is probable that it contained men superior in learning and prudence, skill and experience, to those of any other place; due regard was pald to this circumstance, that the glory of the city and other far more excellent gifts of God might not appear to be undervalued. ln the third place, while the Eastern and Greek Ohurches, and even those in Africa, were agitated by numerous dissensione of opinion among themselves, the Church of Rome was more peaceable and less disturbed.
